Wrenbury
[trigger none]
[vignette dungeons/wrenbury]

Shallow ditches score the hillside in long parallel curves, too regular to be natural, softened by decades of grass and rain into something that could almost be terracing. Almost. But the geometry is wrong for farming -- overlapping arcs, angled to cover approaches, with deep depressions spaced between them like missing teeth in a jaw.

Earthworks. Old ones.

Beyond them, a clutch of market stalls and canvas awnings where no town stands. People move between them -- too many people for a place this far from the road, and dressed too well. A knot of children chases through the tall grass with sticks raised overhead.

You know this place. Not from being here. From a woodcut in a schoolbook, a lesson delivered in monotone by someone who'd never left the city. Wrenbury. The Seventh and Ninth Legions held this ridge for three days against an Iron incursion -- small skirmishers and at least two siege-class striders. The version you learned was mostly arrows and courage. Looking at the depth of the pits they dug for the walkers, half-flooded now and choked with reeds, you suspect the version you learned left things out.

Someone has reconstructed a section of stake-wall near the main path. A man stands beside it, gesturing broadly at a semicircle of onlookers. His voice doesn't carry from here, but his arms are doing a lot of work.

You'd need to get closer to make much sense of it.

